{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:58:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:58:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"255"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/255"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.82,0.05,0.05,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112535"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/255"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3524"},{"type":"tags","id":"3803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112535"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after collapsing while standing up at work. He has been unwell with flu-like symptoms for the past three days. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is usually fit and well, and surfs every weekend.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 60/40 mmHg lying flat, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is a muscular man with tanned skin. After receiving 1L of intravenous normal saline, his blood pressure remains low at 62/43 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Addison\u0027s disease","Dehydration","Septic shock","Acute hypoglycaemia","Diabetes insipidus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features classic for an Addisonian crisis (acute adrenal insufficiency). \u003Cstrong\u003EAddison\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the triad of hypotension resistant to fluid resuscitation, hyponatraemia with hyperkalaemia (due to aldosterone deficiency), and hyperpigmentation (due to increased ACTH production). The crisis was likely precipitated by the physiological stress of his viral illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDehydration\u003C/strong\u003E typically improves with fluid resuscitation, unlike this case where hypotension persisted despite receiving 1L of normal saline. Simple dehydration would also typically cause hypernatraemia rather than hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E, while also potentially resistant to fluid resuscitation, is less likely given the absence of fever or clear source of infection. The characteristic biochemical changes of Addison\u0027s disease would not be present in septic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E alone cannot explain the persistent hypotension or electrolyte abnormalities. While hypoglycaemia can occur in Addison\u0027s disease due to cortisol deficiency, it is not the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E causes hypernatraemia due to free water loss, the opposite of what is seen here. It would also not explain the hyperpigmentation or resistant hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of Addison\u0027s disease can be confirmed with a short synacthen test, but immediate treatment with hydrocortisone and fluid resuscitation should not be delayed if the diagnosis is suspected in an unwell patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Addisonian crisis presents with hypotension that is poorly responsive to fluid resuscitation","Characteristic biochemistry in Addison\u0027s disease includes hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia due to aldosterone deficiency","Hyperpigmentation in Addison\u0027s disease occurs due to increased ACTH production"],"references":["Barthel A, Benker G, Berens K, et al. An Update on Addison\u0027s Disease. Exp Clin Endocrinol Diabetes 2019; 127:165-70."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"255"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19947"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19947"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/be9b8ab1-284c-49c8-bb04-8edbaa3a5a9b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/be9b8ab1-284c-49c8-bb04-8edbaa3a5a9b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":400,"height":82}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T13:38:29+09:30","update